d:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Super Heavy’s 33-engine boostback burn confirmed operational"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Stage separation now a solved variable in reuse timeline"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Full-system reusability edges closer to economic viability"}]]}]]}]}]
e:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["When SpaceX’s Starship lifted off from Starbase on November 19, the real story wasn’t the fire and thunder—it was the quiet confirmation that the most complex part of rocket reuse is becoming routine. The sixth flight test demonstrated what ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.spacex.com/vehicles/starship/","children":"SpaceX’s engineering roadmap"}]," has long promised: a Super Heavy booster executing a nominal ascent, clean stage separation, and a boostback burn with all 33 Raptor engines performing as intended."]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["This wasn’t just another launch. It was the first time the booster’s return trajectory—critical for eventual catch-and-reuse—was validated under full thrust. Unlike prior tests where anomalies derailed post-separation objectives, this flight treated the boostback burn as a ",["$","em",null,{"children":"given"}],", not an experiment. That’s a tectonic shift. For a vehicle designed to be fully reusable, proving the booster can reliably pivot from launch to landing mode is the difference between a prototype and a production system."]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The implications stretch beyond SpaceX. Reusable heavy-lift rockets aren’t just about cutting costs—they’re about changing the economics of orbital infrastructure. If Starship’s booster can be flown, landed, and reflown with minimal refurbishment, the calculus for mega-constellations, lunar bases, and even Mars missions ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.07843","children":"flips from aspirational to operational"}],"."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[["$","$L16",null,{"id":"CMGiNKcVSek","title":"Starship’s sixth flight proves reuse is the real race"}],["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/starships-sixth-flight-proves-reuse-is-the-real-ra/subtitle.jpg","alt":"The milestone that shifts Starship from spectacle to system","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"The milestone that shifts Starship from spectacle to system"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":"What happened, second by second, underscores how far the program has come. At T+0, all 33 Raptors ignited—a feat that still ranks among the most technically demanding in rocketry. By T+2:41, stage separation occurred at ~70 km altitude, with the booster immediately initiating its boostback burn. No engine failures. No unexpected trajectories. Just a machine doing what machines are supposed to do: work."}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["Yet the most significant data point isn’t what ",["$","em",null,{"children":"did"}]," happen, but what ",["$","em",null,{"children":"didn’t"}],". There were no unplanned disassembly events, no last-second aborts, no mysteries to unravel in telemetry. For a test flight, that’s the definition of success. The ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.faa.gov/space/stakeholder_engagement/spacex_starship","children":"FAA’s post-launch assessment"}]," noted no major anomalies—a rarity in Starship’s history and a sign that the vehicle’s design iterations are converging on stability."]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The next frontier? Proving the same reliability for Starship’s upper stage, which still needs to demonstrate controlled re-entry and landing. But the booster’s performance removes the biggest variable from the equation. As ","$L17"," note, ‘Reuse isn’t about flying twice. It’s about flying ","$L18","—and this test is the first domino.’"]}],"\n","$L19"]}]
